With just days to go and probably most Conservative party member votes now being cast by post, a Liz Truss victory seems almost inevitable. Rishi Sunak has even been posited as a member of her cabinet team, notably his attacks against her have toned down in recent days, relying instead upon allies to make such attacks, although less barbed than early on in the contest. Rishi Sunak's chances of victor are now incredibly remote, although some kind of significant Truss error, misguided statement etc will potentially offer him a chance theoretically.

I am basing this on latest YouGov poll. https://docs.cdn.yougov.com/zrayuiymnm/P_Sky_ConservativePartyMembers_August2022_w.pdf . If it is accurate, it has interesting implications.57% have already voted (68% Truss, 31% Sunak) . That means of the100% of voters, 39% have already voted for Truss and 18% for Sunak. Sunak would need 77% of the remaining voters to win. 29% of the remaining voters say they will vote for him. 26% percent say they don't know. Even if all the "don't knows" vote for him he can't win. I appreciate that polls may not be accurate and things may change, but this suggests Truss will win.
This is @Baytree . I am basing this on latest YouGov poll. https://docs.cdn.yougov.com/zrayuiymnm/P_Sky_ConservativePartyMembers_August2022_w.pdf . If it is accurate, it has interesting implications.

Today is the day of the ballots have been sent to members and there does not seem to have been a huge shift towards Sunak. Apparently most Tory members vote early, and, whilst they can change their votes, they tend not to.

Truss got endorsed by Ben Wallace. I gave Sunak the edge in my previous forecast due to his excellent personal branding, however, this vote is not determined by the broader public, but by Tory party members. They will sooner turn to Truss as Boris-continuity candidate - but it's difficult to call. Popular opinion is quickly shifting towards Truss, but Sunak could still win if his behind-the-scenes-work is better than his campaigning. Ben Wallace's endorsement, however, indicates that this is not the case.
Conservative MPs are now increasingly backing Liz Truss. It is therefore increasingly likely that Rishi Sunak will pull out if the race to avoid the potential embarrassment of a heavy loss.
Sunak and Truss are the final two candidates and Truss may have a bit more credibility because she was not implicated in the UK Covid party scandal as Sunak was.

Ben Wallace endorsement for Truss is potentially an important issue. But the pro-Johnson stance, adopted by Truss, seems to have won her a lot of support, during the first 'hustings' in Leeds. But I won't read too much into Leeds, which is almost home turf for Truss as she went to school there.
Liz Truss has upped her game and the PM position is hers to lose. She is the Boris Johnson continuity candidate and is dog-whistling effectively to all the biases of the party.

Based on current polling

At this point, Truss appears to be set to win the membership by some margin according to various polls. She also appears to be popular with a further right faction of the party, who have, in recent years, been more influential than the One Nation group. Her policies are also more 'traditionally conservative', especially with regard to the economy. Despite relatively poor debate performances and not possessing as much charisma as Sunak, she is still well in the lead and looks set to stay this way, especially with the Daily Mail backing her. With that being said, one cannot entirely rule out a major gaffe, scandal, or moment of realisation that could lead to a Sunak premiership.
The 2 remaining candidates.

Slightly reducing Rishi Sunak, in favour of Liz Truss. There have been no new reliable polls of conservative members, but Truss has been favourably received in comparison to Sunak (or more, Sunak has received more press criticism) following the two completed and one partially completed head-to-head debates. Conservative members will recieve their postal ballot papers next week, this seems a sensible time for the next review.

Penny Mordaunt appears to have the strongest combination of Conservative party MP and membership support. Rishi Sunak is facing newspaper editorial pressure which will be of greater importance to membership voting. Liz Truss seems to the Daily Mail pick - this will be important to MPs and members alike.

After round 1 of voting there are 6 candidates with very diverse backgrounds. 3 candidates are named in this question and 3 were not giving weight to the yes, someone else answer. However 2 of the top 3 are on the named list.

Hunt and Zahawi out; Sunak falling just seems inevitable. Mordaunt has broader appeal to the Conservative MPs, and Badenoch and Truss could both surprise people.

Persistent poor polling for Sunak from party members. He is a slick communicator and should make the final two with MP backing. I would expect him to narrow the gap in the final contest, but members still have a strong affinity to Johnson that shouldn't be underestimated.

Reducing the 'someone else' option as it is effectively only Penny Mordaunt in there as a realistic contender among the Conservative party membership. with Liz Truss gaining important backing from senior Conservative MPs, Penny Mordaunt's challenge does become harder.

The following appear like they should matter, but I suspect have little direct effect on the outcome: party rules that prevent another no-confidence vote, bi-election results tomorrow, or the findings of the privileges committee. I believe the party will not make a change unless they can coalesce around a plausible alternative leader first, or time forces their hand with an imminent General Election loss.

Adjusting down Sunak and increasing Tugendhat, who seems to be doing better. But Boris still looks most likely to be leader owing to his winning of the no confidence vote in June. This will not be with its challenges though.

I didn’t realise that current rules mean that there has to be a 12 month wait before a second confidence vote. While there are rumblings that the 1922 committee might try to change this to 6 months this will take time and they don’t yet have the votes to do this. Even if they changed the rules today the vote couldn’t happen before the end of the year when this question resolves.
Ben Wallace was the most interesting name filed under "someone else", it's amazing you brought him into play so early. However, apparently Wallace has ruled himeself out of standing.
Johnson seems to be finally on the way out by January anyway,
Feeble Tory response after confidence vote.

Boris won his vote of no confidence, but his outlook looks bad given that May, Major, and Thatcher all left the job shortly (~months) after better performances in a vote of no confidence against them. The next "deadline" for Boris staying/leaving will be around the tory party conference which takes place between the 2nd and 5th of October, leaving time for a leadership contest that would begin around then (possibly before). This also leaves the race to be the next PM quite open.

The slim margin of victory has left the PM on shaky ground after a significant portion of his party turned their backs on him. It means that, while he has survived, for now, his medium-term future remains uncertain.

After the no confidence vote it will be quite a surprise if Jonson makes it to the end of the year. We are just waiting for an alternate leader to step out of the shadows to bring the alternative into focus. As Jeremy Hunt has revealed he is one of the no confidence vote group, then in suggests he might be interested, so will have to put some possibility on him.
I think Johnson is likely to struggle on, but it is not entirely certain.

The Lib Dems are laughable. A VAT cut will not make the economy grow. It is imprudent when the Chancellor has been forced to initiate other accomodative fiscal measures to deal with the price of energy.
Now that the no confidence hurdle is passed Bojo is safe for a year and so is England.

Boris Johnson surviving a leadership challenge remains my primary case. I do not think it likely, given the poor selection of replacements, that he will fall to a no confidence vote, and I do not think it likely that he will resign by choice. An election can be postponed for a further year beyond the end date of this prediction, and so there's no pressing need to pull the trigger and replace him when he can soak up further unpleasantness.

Slightly increasing likelihood as 1) small number of Con MPs indicating their desire for Johnson to go (but still a narrow segment of the party), 2) revelations of further parties, 3) inc pressure to expedite Parl investigation and 4) a betting market suggesting a 1/3 chance he’ll go this year ( slightly different to this question)
Gray didn’t say much new.
No further fines key.

Slashing odds as time progresses and because there are fewer fines than expected and conservative reaction to Conservative losses at local elections not sustained publicly. But Sue Gray report and Commons investigation mean I think there’s a reasonable chance of things spinning out uncontrollably despite the bigger issues of impact of the economy and Ukraine. Also Johnson always has capacity to do something (else) that would get him sacked by MPs and less resilience now. But the Lack of an obvious successor also reduces prospect of challenge.
The Local Election results are still being announced, but so far the important takeaways seem to be:

Johnson is at risk again, but it is hard to see who is well placed to win a leadership contest. Gove is now the most credible with Sunak's fall from grace but of course he likely has some skeletons of his own. I still find it hard to see Truss becoming PM, but I would have said the same about May so maybe I shouldn't rule it out.
Boris Johnson looks as rattled as in February.

I’m uncertain whether economic challenges will hasten or delay his departure but on balance more likely to delay beyond the window of this projection.

Increasingly coming around to the view that ConHome polls are the only actual *metric* worth watching on this question. The rest is a mix of common sense and vibes.
None of the above are electable and more likely to lose the election to Kier Starmer. And why the hell is Penny Mordaunt not in the list?

Downrating my earlier estimate of Boris' survival in the light of new inflation projections, likewise downrating the potential for Sunak to replace him as inflation-presiding Chancellors are not exactly hot political property.

Very likely that no leadership contest will come this year. If it does, Sunak seems the obvious successor and may run with Hunt (hence he's on 0%.) Tugendhat is popular albeit inexperienced, Javid is an outsider, Ukraine has made Truss appear weaker.
With forthcoming inflation and other costs (e.g. NI increase), Rishi's star is waning from the days of the Treasury's Covid largesse, and this will further be underscored at the Budget.
Political climate as it stands, I don't see Boris willingly stepping down. Genuinely unsure if government has anyone more capable at this time.

Ben Wallace isn't listed as a candidate in this list, so I'm upping my estimate of "Someone else". Being Defence Secretary during a European war is a good platform from which to demonstrate leadership abilities, and potentially launch a bid.

However, also adjusted the three contenders I feel have chance of winning, with Rishi still being favourite but Truss closer behind given her role internationally making her more visible and potentially “Prime Ministerial”.
Johnson will hang on unless the local election are a compete disaster.

I don’t think Johnson will survive much past the May local elections. And there is plenty of time before the end of the year. I feel there is a lot of quiet debate and argument about what direction the party should take going on in the background that would do them no good making too public, especially before the elections, so I think by then whoever it willing to take it on might step forward.
As per Q2, currently not likely there’ll be a successful challenge

The Conservatives will throw him out when it becomes clear that he cannot win the next election. They may not like his actions and dislike him personally but at the end of the day they want to be in power, and the red wall voters that he won from Labour at the last election seem unmoved by the revelations. In fact the people who like him, like him more when he is under pressure from the media, and the traditional Tories will vote Tory anyway. The 10% is because no-one can know what other revelations will fall out before August as he is a serial philanderer and has only a glancing relationship with the truth.

The next 12 months will be very rough for the UK, Johnson will continue in the post and take the hits. Only when things calm / improve will the contest start for a replacement. Sunak should get the post with his experience and his ability to project a stateman like image to the public.

Boris Johnson’s waning popularity and Rishi Sunak apparent (I know nothing to the contrary) ‘clean’ image and financial acumen make him an excellent replacement and a new chapter for the Conservatives.

John Major has called for Tory MPs to vote with Labour in a no confidence vote. Rishi Sunak ticks the minority box for a party that needs to draw more minority voters, while he also has far less past scandals or controversies compared to the other prominent candidates.
Truss just made a stupid comment to the Russian FM about Voronezh & Rostov

The Conservative party will not break with Oxbridge traditions, especially at the undergrad level. I am also doubtful that the party will elect a person of color as leader. Gove, Hunt, and Raab most easily fit the bill. Truss also fits the bill, but she too easily is parodied. She has not been impressive as foreign secretary, though she cannot be entirely discounted given her earlier successes. The party doesn't choose the cabinet, which is why she succeeds, whereas the party does choose the leader and I just can't imagine the party going for her. Tugendhat, likewise, seems unlikely inasmuch as 1) his undergrad is from Bristol and 2) he doesn't seem to get much coverage, relative to others, in the press.

I think 1 January 2023 is a bit soon given there is no clear contender to replace Johnson and the party will not want a very public process where many factions are competing. I think over the course of 2022 there will be a build up toward a late 2022 or early 2023 process.
Things arent bad enough to change
Penny Mordant, there is not much chance she will end up leader but not no chance especially with her strong defense credentials, ability to play to the party base etc
Gove, Raab, Hunt Truss: Good old Conservative names. Sunak: An "interesting" persona to divert memory from B. Johnson. Someone else - have to place a small bet on surprise.

B Johnson has lost the trust of the electorate. Unless he can pull some wins out of the Brexit debacle he will not survive another year. Depending on performance in her current role - as at Feb 22 - Liz Truss looks to have the authority to run and achieve the leadership. Ditto R Sunak although he is somewhat tarnished by his association with the current leadership. The party may well want to elect someone who stands outside the current inner circle. Could T May return?

Boris continues to demonstrate the determination to stay until pushed. There is a perception that Boris campaigns well and can win an election, and with plenty of time to allow current waters to pass under the bridge.
